  "response": "## Three IA findings — merge recommendations\n\n**1. `route_metadata_drift` (crime_00020) — `/settings/billing`** → **warn**\n\nThe route is labelled four different ways: file `billing.tsx`, component `PricingPage`, metadata title `Plans`, `<title>` tag `Subscription`, sidebar `Billing`, registry `Plans`. Nothing here breaks at runtime — users still reach the page — but every label an agent picks as \"the canonical one\" will be contradicted by another file. Worth fixing before someone renames the wrong thing, but not severe enough to block a merge that doesn't touch this route. If the PR being reviewed *is* renaming this route, escalate to block.\n\n**2. `duplicated_navigation_source` (crime_00018) — `/settings/billing` in two nav files** → **warn**\n\n`src/nav/registry.ts` calls it \"Plans\"; `src/nav/sidebar.ts` calls it \"Billing\". Same destination, two labels, two source files. An agent updating one will leave the other stale — which is exactly the drift in finding #1. This is the upstream cause: consolidating nav sources fixes part of the route-metadata drift for free. Warn rather than block because the inconsistency is already shipped; fixing it is a follow-up, not a gate.\n\n**3. `docs_code_drift` (crime_00022) — `docs/teams.md` → `./setup.md`** → **ignore** (for merge), file as a docs cleanup\n\nSeverity `low`, confidence `0.9`, one broken local link. It misleads anyone following the doc, but it doesn't affect code correctness, build, or runtime. Don't block a merge on it. Fix it in a docs sweep — or, if the current PR touches `docs/teams.md`, fix it inline.\n\n---\n\n**Suggested order if you fix all three:** consolidate the nav source first (#2), then realign route metadata against the now-single label (#1), then patch the doc link (#3). #2 → #1 is the natural sequence because #1's evidence literally cites the two nav files from #2.",
